4'),(10375,'creator',15,'Drake, Patricia S','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10376,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10377,'description',15,'Published by SAGE Publications','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10378,'date',15,'2001-07','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10379,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10380,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10381,'identifier',15,'Drake, Patricia S (2001) Mathematics and all that : Who teaches the number stuff? Active Learning in Higher Education, 2 (1). pp. 46-52. ISSN 1469-7874','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10382,'relation',15,'10.1177/1469787401002001004','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10383,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/4/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:4'),(10384,'title',15,'Testing teachers: perspectives on a pilot Numeracy Skills test','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10385,'creator',15,'Drake, Patricia S','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10386,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10387,'description',15,'From May 2001 all teachers qualifying in England must be successful in computer-based skills tests in numeracy and literacy. The first test to be developed was the QTS Skills Test in Numeracy, which was a paper and pencil test taken on 1 June 2000 by approximately 22,000 trainee teachers. In this article I argue that the pilot test signals an unjustified departure from performance-based assessment, provides an example of inconsistency between national imperatives and teacher certification and was not robust. A small study of trainee teachers of secondary English was undertaken to explore perceptions of professional numeracy in relation to their experience in training, what was tested in the skills test and what is known about testing mathematics through questions set in pseudo-real contexts. I conclude that theoretically it would be difficult to devise an appropriate examination type test of professional numeracy and that in the event the pilot test was not successful.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10388,'publisher',15,'Taylor & Francis','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10389,'date',15,'2002-07-01','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10390,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10391,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10392,'identifier',15,'Drake, Patricia S (2002) Testing teachers: perspectives on a pilot Numeracy Skills test. Assessment in Education, 9 (2). pp. 205-220. ISSN 0969-594X','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10393,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/5/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:5'),(10394,'title',15,'Becoming a Teaching Assistant: A Research Based Guide for TA s and Those Working with Them.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10395,'creator',15,'Drake, Patricia S','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10396,'publisher',15,'Paul Chapman Publishing.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10397,'date',15,'2004','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10398,'type',15,'Book','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10399,'type',15,'NonPeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10400,'identifier',15,'Drake, Patricia S (2004) Becoming a Teaching Assistant: A Research Based Guide for TA s and Those Working with Them. Paul Chapman Publishing., London, UK. ISBN 9780761943563','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10401,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/6/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:6'),(10402,'title',15,'Developing educational leadership: using evidence for policy and practice','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10403,'creator',15,'Sebba, Judy C','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10404,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10405,'publisher',15,'Paul Chapman','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10406,'contributor',15,'Anderson , L','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10407,'contributor',15,'Bennett, N','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10408,'date',15,'2003','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10409,'type',15,'Book Chapter or Section','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10410,'type',15,'NonPeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10411,'identifier',15,'Sebba, Judy C (2003) Developing educational leadership: using evidence for policy and practice. In: Anderson , L and Bennett, N (eds.) Evidence-informed policy and practice in educational leadership and management: applications and controversies. Paul Chapman, London, pp. 11-25. ISBN 978-0761949381','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10412,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/9/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:9'),(10413,'title',15,'Developing evidence-informed policy and practice in education','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10414,'creator',15,'Sebba, Judy C','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10415,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10416,'publisher',15,'Open University Press','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10417,'contributor',15,'Thomas, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10418,'contributor',15,'Pring, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10419,'date',15,'2004','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10420,'type',15,'Book Chapter or Section','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10421,'type',15,'NonPeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10422,'identifier',15,'Sebba, Judy C (2004) Developing evidence-informed policy and practice in education. In: Thomas, G and Pring, R (eds.) Evidence-based Practice in Education (Conducting Educational Research). Conducting Educational Research . Open University Press, pp. 34-44. ISBN 978-0335213351','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10423,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/10/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:10'),(10424,'title',15,'Subject perspectives in mentoring','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10425,'creator',15,'Drake, Patricia S','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10426,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10427,'description',15,'This book brings together the work of teams in six universities involved in school-based partnerships for teacher education. The focus is on the distinctive work of school-based teacher educators, the teacher mentors in the partnership schools, both primary and secondary. The Editors have coordinated the project, a national conference and the book itself, writing introductory and concluding chapters and synthesising the work of the six teams. The teams are from Oxford University, the Manchester Metropolitan University, Keele, Sussex, Swansea and Leicester Universities. All involved in school-based teacher education - whether as mentors, teacher trainers in higher education, school senior management, advisers, or inspectors - should find the range of experience presented here invaluable in their own work.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10428,'publisher',15,'Fulton','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10429,'contributor',15,'McIntyre, D','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10430,'contributor',15,'Hagger, H','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10431,'date',15,'1996','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10432,'type',15,'Book Chapter or Section','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10433,'type',15,'NonPeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10434,'identifier',15,'Drake, Patricia S (1996) Subject perspectives in mentoring. In: McIntyre, D and Hagger, H (eds.) Mentors in schools: developing the profession of teaching. Fulton, London, 56 - 74. ISBN 9781853464119','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10435,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/11/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:11'),(10436,'title',15,'Concepts of Competence','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10437,'creator',15,'Eraut, Michael R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10438,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10439,'description',15,'An analysis of everyday use of the term competence\' is followed by a literature review. Some authors treat competence as a socially situated conceptthe ability to perform tasks and roles to the expected standardleaving its precise meaning to be negotiated by stakeholders in a macro-or micro-political context. Others treat competence as individually situated, a personal capability or characteristic. This latter concept is labelled capability\' and its vital relationship with socially-defined Competence is analysed. The importance for practice of representations of competence and for professional preparation of models of capability is discussed.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10440,'date',15,'1998','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10441,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10442,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10443,'identifier',15,'Eraut, Michael R (1998) Concepts of Competence. Journal of Interprofessional Care, 12 (2). 127 - 139. ISSN 1356-1820','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10444,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/12/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:12'),(10445,'title',15,'Headteachers\' knowledge, practice and mode of cognition','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10446,'creator',15,'Eraut, Michael R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10447,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10448,'publisher',15,'Chapman','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10449,'contributor',15,'Bush, T','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10450,'contributor',15,'Bell, L','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10451,'contributor',15,'Bolam, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10452,'contributor',15,'Glatter, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10453,'contributor',15,'Ribbins, P','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10454,'date',15,'1999','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10455,'type',15,'Book Chapter or Section','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10456,'type',15,'NonPeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10457,'identifier',15,'Eraut, Michael R (1999) Headteachers\' knowledge, practice and mode of cognition. In: Bush, T, Bell, L, Bolam, R, Glatter, R and Ribbins, P (eds.) Educational management: redefining theory policy and practice. Chapman, 114 - 126. ISBN 9780761965558','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10458,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/13/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:13'),(10459,'title',15,'Non-formal Learning and Tacit Knowledge in Professional Work','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10460,'creator',15,'Eraut, Michael R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10461,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10462,'description',15,'Bachground. This paper explores the conceptual and methodological problems arising from several empirical investigations of professional education and learning in the workplace. Aims. 1. To clarify the multiple meanings accorded to terms such as \'non-formal learning\', \'implicit learning\' and \'tacit knowledge\', their theoretical assumptions and the range of phenomena to which they refer. 2. To discuss their implications for professional practice. Method. A largely theoretical analysis of issues and phenomena arising from empirical investigations. Analysis. The author\'s typology of non-formal learning distinguishes between implicit learning, reactive on-the-spot learning and deliberative learning. The significance of the last is commonly overemphasised. The problematic nature of tacit knowledge is discussed with respect to both detecting it and representing it. Three types of tacit knowledge are discussed: tacit understanding of people and situations, routinised actions and the tacit rules that underpin intuitive decision-making. They come together when professional performance involves sequences of routinised action punctuated by rapid intuitive decisions based on tacit understanding of the situation. Four types of process are involved-reading the situation, making decisions, overt activity and metacognition-and three modes of cognition-intuitive, analytic and deliberative. The balance between these modes depends on time, experience and complexity. Where rapid action dominates, periods of deliberation are needed to maintain critical control. Finally the role of both formal and informal social knowledge is discussed; and it is argued that situated learning often leads not to local conformity but to greater individual variation as people\'s careers take them through a series of different contexts. This abstract necessarily simplifies a more complex analysis in the paper itself.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10463,'date',15,'2000-03','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10464,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10465,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10466,'identifier',15,'Eraut, Michael R (2000) Non-formal Learning and Tacit Knowledge in Professional Work. British Journal of Educational Psychology, 70 (1). 113 - 136. ISSN 0007-0998','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10467,'relation',15,'http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/bpsoc/bjep/2000/00000070/00000001/art00008','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10468,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/14/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:14'),(10469,'title',15,'The Development of Knowledge and Skills at Work','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10470,'creator',15,'Eraut, Michael R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10471,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10472,'publisher',15,'Policy Press ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10473,'contributor',15,'Coffield, Frank','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10474,'date',15,'2000','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10475,'type',15,'Book Chapter or Section','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10476,'type',15,'NonPeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10477,'identifier',15,'Eraut, Michael R (2000) The Development of Knowledge and Skills at Work. In: Coffield, Frank (ed.) Differing visions of the Learning Society: Research findings. ESRC learning society series, 1 . Policy Press , Bristol, 231 - 262. ISBN 9781861342300','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10478,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/15/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:15'),(10479,'title',15,'Menus for choosy diners','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10480,'creator',15,'Eraut, Michael R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10481,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10482,'description',15,'The present paper uses one of Michael Huberman\'s lesser known but most important papers to address the critical issue of teachers\' attention. How do professionals handle competing demands on their attention in busy, crowded, \'hot action\' situations? It argues that finding time to monitor and respond to people and events in a rapidly changing environment requires routines that keep things going with minimal demands on one\'s attention; and that \'hot action\' decision-making is rapid and intuitive rather than deliberative or explicitly evidence based. The present paper focuses on the unrealistic expectations of those who urge teachers to give high levels of attention to individual pupils, whether they be child-centred philosophers, reflectors in action or advocates for matching instruction to psychometrically defined youngsters. These ideologically or politically attractive perspectives on teaching merely disguise the reality of a classroom discourse that strives for instructional compliance. Teachers\' knowledge of pupils is constructed by the largely unconscious aggregation of memories of episodes in which they paid or gave attention to a child; and this knowledge is drawn on rapidly and intuitively in class. Such knowledge is inevitably fallible and biased, but no more so than more \'objective\' constructions. Its great advantage is its usability. Finally, it argues that common approaches to teacher education develop coping mechanisms for classroom control before student teachers have developed an experience-based understanding of how best to support children\'s learning or, better still, how best to enable children to support each other\'s learning.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10483,'date',15,'2002','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10484,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10485,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10486,'identifier',15,'Eraut, Michael R (2002) Menus for choosy diners. Teachers and Teaching: Theory and Practice, 8 (3/4). pp. 371-379. ISSN 1354-0602','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10487,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/135406002100000503','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10488,'relation',15,'10.1080/135406002100000503','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10489,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/20/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:20'),(10490,'title',15,'Workplace-focused learning: perspectives on continuing professional education and human resource development','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10491,'creator',15,'Eraut, Michael R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10492,'creator',15,'Bierma, L','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10493,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10494,'description',15,'The problem and the solution. Learning in the workplace is a major focus for both continuing professional education and human resource development. Yet too often providers and researchers in both areas pay little attention to the learning that actually happens within the work context. In this article, learning in the workplace is analyzed through an examination of the history, assumptions, stakeholders, foci, approaches, and issues in continuing professional education and human resource development. This analysis leads to suggestions for an increased focus on learning.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10495,'date',15,'2004-02','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10496,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10497,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10498,'identifier',15,'Eraut, Michael R and Bierma, L (2004) Workplace-focused learning: perspectives on continuing professional education and human resource development. Advances in Developing Human Resources, 6 (1). pp. 52-68. ISSN 1523-4223','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10499,'relation',15,'http://adh.sagepub.com/cgi/reprint/6/1/52','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10500,'relation',15,'10.1177/1523422303260859','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10501,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/25/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:25'),(10502,'title',15,'A Case of Learning Mathematics the Hard Way as a Teaching Assistant','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10503,'creator',15,'Drake, Patricia S','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10504,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10505,'description',15,'This paper develops early data from a qualitative longitudinal study of the first cohort of five students making the transition from teaching assistant in secondary school to specialist teacher of secondary mathematics. Data from a second cohort of four women and one man starting in 2003 is less complete, but used as appropriate. Bernstein\'s work on subject classification frames an argument that this student group navigates simultaneously two mathematics discourses: hard university mathematics, and everyday mathematics as experienced by the lower ability school pupils that the students support. This raises questions about the purpose and scope of the students work in school with respect to their mathematics learning, and vice versa. The study of conventional mathematics undergraduates for the ESRC (Macrae, Brown, and Rodd, 2003) provides a foil against which to compare approaches to learning mathematics, raising the possibility of a rethink of pre-requisite pre-qualification, and potential relations between university mathematics and work-place learning in secondary schools.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10506,'date',15,'2005-04','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10507,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10508,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10509,'format',15,'text/plain','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10510,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/37/1/Drake_RME7_revised_following_comments_.doc','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10511,'identifier',15,'Drake, Patricia S (2005) A Case of Learning Mathematics the Hard Way as a Teaching Assistant. Research in Mathematics Education, 7 (1). pp. 19-31. ISSN 1479-4802','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10512,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/14794800008520143','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10513,'relation',15,'10.1080/14794800008520143','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10514,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/37/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:37'),(10515,'title',15,'Undergraduate Mathematics Diversified for Non-standard Entrants - Whatever Next! A Case of Teaching Assistants and the Curriculum','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10516,'creator',15,'Drake, Patricia S','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10517,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10518,'description',15,'This paper draws upon data from a longitudinal study of the first cohort of five students making the transition from teaching assistant in secondary school to specialist teacher of secondary mathematics via a new full-time honours degree in Mathematics Education Studies beginning in September 2002. Data from a second cohort of four women and one man starting in 2003 is less complete, but used as appropriate. To complete the degree each student must necessarily continue to work as a teaching assistant, and must complete some assessed work in their school setting. The study is thus located within theorised literature of widening participation, student choice, and learning mathematics. It is timely in view of government policy of a ??remodelled school workforce?? (DfES, 2004) whereby the stated intention is to complement a reduced cadre of qualified teachers with an enhanced number of staff supporting teaching and learning. I argue, using Bernstein??s work (1996) on subject classification, this student group represents a different type of learner, navigating simultaneously two mathematics discourses: ??hard?? university mathematics, and ??everyday mathematics?? as experienced by the lower ability school pupils that the students support when at work. Widening participation rhetoric focuses on enticing people into learning who would not otherwise be there (Hillage and Aston, 2001). This account relates to people who, despite being unqualified are already in educational institutions, i.e. schools, through their work. These are people who are ??pre-disposed?? favourably towards higher education (see for example Billet, 2001), and for whom progression is what is desired. The students have undergone a long, and autodidactical preparation for university study, illustrated in a variety of ways through previous personal and professional engagement with learning. The first group were aged between 35 - 49 on entry to the university, and all working as teaching assistants in three schools, two in each of two schools, and one in a third. None had higher than Grade B Intermediate GCSE in mathematics, but all had qualifications gained through continuing education as adults: in counselling, embroidery, art, design, numeracy, literacy and computer qualifications between them. In comparison with ??traditional?? mathematics undergraduates1, i.e. higher than average A-level points scores on entry, and mainly following on straight from school, the first group of students have extremely limited mathematics qualifications. None has any parents, brothers or sisters that had attended university, and only one has graduates in her immediate family: her husband and daughter. In terms of national data on student populations as a whole (UCAS, Labour Force Survey, Office for National Statistics, 2004) this group is older than almost three-quarters of the undergraduate population and in a lower social class than half of them. The second group show some differences from the first, not in so far as their mathematics qualifications, but in the fact that two of them are already graduates of other subjects. Nevertheless, students are progressing through the programme, between them achieving the full range of marks, and, unlike traditional mathematics students, so far there has been no drop-out. These students exemplify a different type of mathematics learner, those for who mathematics has never been easy, have never been recognised as talented, and who have developed as a consequence successful strategies for dealing with the practically inevitable difficulties. They are people with specific graduate professional ambitions entering the academy with low level formal mathematics qualifications. These distinctions are forcing a rethink of what success in mathematics means, what may be useful pre-requisites in terms of pre-qualification, and the potential relationship between university learning of mathematics alongside work-place learning, in this case in a secondary school mathematics department. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10519,'publisher',15,'Centre for Continuing Education, University of Sussex in conjunction with the Standing Conference on University Teaching and Research in the Education of Adults, SCUTREA','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10520,'contributor',15,'Coare, Pam','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10521,'contributor',15,'Armstrong, Paul','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10522,'contributor',15,'Boice, Mike','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10523,'contributor',15,'Morrice, Linda','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10524,'date',15,'2005','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10525,'type',15,'Book Chapter or Section','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10526,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10527,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10528,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/40/1/A_CASE_OF_LEARNING_MATHEMATICS_THE_HARD_WAY_AS_A_TEACHING_ASSISTANT.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10529,'identifier',15,'Drake, Patricia S (2005) Undergraduate Mathematics Diversified for Non-standard Entrants - Whatever Next! A Case of Teaching Assistants and the Curriculum. In: Coare, Pam, Armstrong, Paul, Boice, Mike and Morrice, Linda (eds.) Diversity and difference in lifelong learning: proceedings 35th annual conference SCUTREA. Centre for Continuing Education, University of Sussex in conjunction with the Standing Conference on University Teaching and Research in the Education of Adults, SCUTREA, Brighton, England, pp. 75-85. ISBN 9780904242508','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10530,'relation',15,'http://www.leeds.ac.uk/educol/documents/142021.doc','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10531,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/40/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:40'),(10532,'title',15,'The Effects of Pupil Grouping: Literature Review','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:41'),(10533,'creator',15,'Sebba, Judy','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:41'