ul Schooling: Ghanaian Teachers\' Understanding of Learning, Teaching and Assessment','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10652,'creator',15,'Akyeampong, Albert K','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10653,'creator',15,'Ampiah , J.G. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10654,'creator',15,'Pryor, J','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10655,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10656,'description',15,'This article reports on an empirical study exploring Ghanaian teachers\' understandings of teaching, learning and assessment. It argues that received views of poorly trained teachers with untheorized and badly reasoned professional practices may mask a more complex situation. In defining learning, teachers in the study reproduced models consistent with transmission or behaviouristic theories. However, when asked to describe their most successful experiences, teachers\' understandings were more in accord with social constructivism. Also, their aspiration towards interactive models of classroom assessment was circumscribed by the normal context of assessment discourse and by bureaucratic requirements. The article concludes that, given the right circumstances, teachers can reflect on their experiences and produce a more sophisticated account of teaching and learning. It suggests ways in which in-service work might make use of these insights, recommending further attention to the discursive frames of teachers\' professional reflections within dialogue and active engagement through school-based coaching. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10657,'date',15,'2006','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10658,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10659,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10660,'identifier',15,'Akyeampong, Albert K, Ampiah , J.G. and Pryor, J (2006) A vision of Successful Schooling: Ghanaian Teachers\' Understanding of Learning, Teaching and Assessment. Comparative Education, 42 (2). pp. 155-176. ISSN 0305-0068','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10661,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/03050060600627936 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10662,'relation',15,'10.1080/03050060600627936 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10663,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/52/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:52'),(10664,'title',15,'Life Expectancy of Shingle Beaches: Measuring in Situ Abrasion','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10665,'creator',15,'Dornbusch, Uwe','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10666,'creator',15,'Williams, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10667,'creator',15,'Robinson, D','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10668,'creator',15,'Moses, C.A.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10669,'subject',15,'QE Geology','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10670,'subject',15,'GB Physical geography','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10671,'subject',15,'GC Oceanography','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10672,'description',15,'In situ abrasion of shingle beach material is a neglected area of study in coastal geomorphology, with reduction in beach volumes normally attributed to longshore and offshore drift. Results from field abrasion experiments conducted on flint shingle beaches on the East Sussex coast, southern England, show that in situ reductions in volume of beach material may be more significant than has been thought. Two beaches composed almost entirely of flint shingle were seeded with hard quartzite from a Devon beach and less resistant limestone from a South Wales beach that are readily distinguishable from the flint. The seeding commenced in January 2001. The pebbles, similar in size and shape to the natural flint shingle, were left in the surf zone at two sites. Prior to exposure the pebbles were engraved with a code number and weighed. At regular intervals those that could be re-found were re-weighed and returned to the beach. Abrasion rates were calculated for each pebble as percentage weight loss per tide. By the end of October 2001, more than 700 measurements of abrasion rates had been made from a total of 431 pebbles. Average limestone abrasion rates (0.0266% loss of weight per tide) were three times greater than those of quartzite (0.0082% per tide). Measurable abrasion rates were recorded over just a few tidal cycles, not only in severe wave conditions but also in much calmer weather. The maximum abrasion rates recorded exceeded 1% per tide for limestone.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10673,'publisher',15,'Coastal Education and Research Foundation','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10674,'date',15,'2002','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10675,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10676,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10677,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10678,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/60/1/2002%2D04%2DLife_expectancy_of_shingle_beaches%2DJ_of_Coastal_Research%2DDornbusch.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10679,'identifier',15,'Dornbusch, Uwe, Williams, R, Robinson, D and Moses, C.A. (2002) Life Expectancy of Shingle Beaches: Measuring in Situ Abrasion. Journal of Coastal Research, Specia. pp. 249-255. ISSN 0749-0208','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10680,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/60/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:60'),(10681,'title',15,'Soft copy Photogrammetry to Measure Shore Platform Erosion on Decadal Time Scales','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10682,'creator',15,'Dornbusch, Uwe','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10683,'creator',15,'Moses, Cherith','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10684,'creator',15,'Robinson, David','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10685,'creator',15,'Williams, Rendel','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10686,'subject',15,'QE Geology','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10687,'subject',15,'GB Physical geography','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10688,'description',15,'Shore platform erosion is considered a driving mechanism for cliff recession on many rocky coasts and, in the vicinity of sea defence structures, a threat to their stability, yet the spatial pattern of platform erosion, as well as the rate of lowering, is poorly documented. Measurements based on techniques such as the micro-erosion metre or laser scanner, though highly accurate for short time scales and specific locations, are difficult to extrapolate in space and time. They also fail to record meso-scale changes such as block removal. This paper describes a technique to quantify spatial and temporal changes and presents first results.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10689,'date',15,'2005-07','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10690,'type',15,'Conference or Workshop Item','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10691,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10692,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10693,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/65/1/2005%2DDornbusch%2Det%2Dal_softcopy_photogrammetry.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10694,'identifier',15,'Dornbusch, Uwe, Moses, Cherith, Robinson, David and Williams, Rendel (2005) Soft copy Photogrammetry to Measure Shore Platform Erosion on Decadal Time Scales. In: CoastGIS \'05 defining and building a marine and coastal spatial data infrastructure : full proceedings, Aberdeen, Scotland, UK, 21-23 Jul 2005, Aberdeen, UK.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10695,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s11852-008-0025-8','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10696,'relation',15,'10.1007/s11852-008-0025-8','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10697,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/65/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:65'),(10698,'title',15,'Chalk Cliff Retreat in East Sussex and Kent 1870s to 2001','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10699,'creator',15,'Dornbusch, U','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10700,'creator',15,'Robinson, D.A','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10701,'creator',15,'Moses, C','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10702,'creator',15,'Williams, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10703,'creator',15,'Costa, S','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10704,'subject',15,'QE Geology','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10705,'subject',15,'GB Physical geography','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10706,'description',15,'The retreat of chalk cliffs fringing the eastern English Channel contributes shingle to the beaches which helps to protect the cliffs and slow down erosion. Conversely, cliff retreat endangers settlements and infrastructure on the clifftop. Rates of retreat have been calculated by a variety of methods over the past century, but no attempt has been made to provide a complete coverage that allows for a true comparison of retreat rates over the entire coastline. Using historic maps and recent orthophotos, cliff retreat rates have been calculated for consecutive 50 m sections of chalk cliff along the English side of the entire eastern English Channel for a period of 125 years. The chalk cliffs of East Sussex erode at an average rate of 0.25 - 0.3 m y?1 while those in Kent at a rate of 0.1 m y?1.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10707,'publisher',15,'Taylor & Francis','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10708,'date',15,'2006','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10709,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10710,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10711,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10712,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/67/1/Dornbusch_coast_1124460539.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10713,'identifier',15,'Dornbusch, U, Robinson, D.A, Moses, C, Williams, R and Costa, S (2006) Chalk Cliff Retreat in East Sussex and Kent 1870s to 2001. Journal of Maps. pp. 71-78. ISSN 1744-5647','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10714,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.4113/jom.2006.46','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10715,'relation',15,'10.4113/jom.2006.46','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10716,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/67/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:67'),(10717,'title',15,'Estimation of Abrasion on Flint Shingle Beaches in East Sussex, UK.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10718,'creator',15,'Dornbusch, U.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10719,'creator',15,'Robinson, D.A.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10720,'creator',15,'Williams, R.B.G.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10721,'creator',15,'Moses, C.A.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10722,'subjec