.ac.uk/70/1/2003%2D05%2DEstimation_of_abrasion_loss_on__flint_shingle_beach%2DCoastal_Sediments_03_Florida%2DDornbusch.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10731,'identifier',15,'Dornbusch, U., Robinson, D.A., Williams, R.B.G. and Moses, C.A. (2003) Estimation of Abrasion on Flint Shingle Beaches in East Sussex, UK. In: Proceedings of the International Conference on Coastal Sediments 2003. CD-ROM Published by World Scientific Publishing Corp. and East Meets West Productions, Corpus Christi, Texas, USA, 18-23 May 2003, Clearwater Beach, Florida.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10732,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/70/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:70'),(10733,'title',15,'The People\'s Liberation Army and the Market Economy','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10734,'creator',15,'Yeung, GKY','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10735,'subject',15,'HX Socialism. Communism. Anarchism','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10736,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10737,'publisher',15,'Macmillan','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10738,'contributor',15,'Benewick, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10739,'contributor',15,'Wingrove, P','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10740,'date',15,'1999','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10741,'type',15,'Book Chapter or Section','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10742,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10743,'identifier',15,'Yeung, GKY (1999) The People\'s Liberation Army and the Market Economy. In: Benewick, R and Wingrove, P (eds.) China in the 1990s. Macmillan, London, UK, pp. 158-168. ISBN 9780333601389','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10744,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/117/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:117'),(10745,'title',15,'Large Firms and Catch-up in a Transitional Cconomy: The Case of Shougang Group in China','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10746,'creator',15,'Nolan, P','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10747,'creator',15,'Yeung, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10748,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10749,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10750,'description',15,'This study examines the possibility of catch-up of the Chinese steel industry, in particular the Shougang Group, with the leading global steel giants. Shougang is one of the four steel companies that have been selected by the Chinese government to constitute the core of the future Chinese steel industry. The contract system at Shougang, which operated from 1979 to 1995, unleashed an extraordinary entrepreneurial energy in the formerly traditional state-run steel plant. In the post-contract system, Shougang\'s range of decision-making independence in respect to the purchase of inputs, its production structure and product marketing has increased substantially compared to the contract system, when the government still controlled many of the key decisions. As a result of institutional constraint, the low value-added steel products dominate Shougang\'s portfolio. To challenge the established giants in the steel industry, Shougang has to divest the loss-making non-core businesses, slowly downsize employment in the core business, raise capital on the stock market and generates the resources for continued upgrading of its steel technology and diversifying its product portfolio.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10751,'date',15,'2001','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10752,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10753,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10754,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10755,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/118/1/Shougang.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10756,'identifier',15,'Nolan, P and Yeung, G (2001) Large Firms and Catch-up in a Transitional Cconomy: The Case of Shougang Group in China. Economics of Planning, 34 (01-02). pp. 159-178. ISSN 0013-0451','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10757,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1023/A:1017504617090','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10758,'relation',15,'10.1023/A:1017504617090','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10759,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/118/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:118'),(10760,'title',15,'Foreign Investment and Socio-economic Development in China: The Case of Dongguan','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10761,'creator',15,'Yeung, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10762,'subject',15,'G Geography (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10763,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10764,'subject',15,'HB Economic theory. Demography','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10765,'subject',15,'JS Local government Municipal government','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10766,'description',15,'Different from the existing literature who focusing on macro-geographical scale (regional or national level), this book investigates the causes and socio-economic effects of foreign direct investment in the Dongguan municipality of southern China during the 1990s. As the first comprehensive research based on primary quantitative and qualitative data undertaken in Dongguan, it is illustrated that the inflow of foreign capital have its desirable and undesirable socio-economic effects. In addition to being the first comprehensive research based on primary quantitative and qualitative data undertaken in Dongguan, the book proposes a dynamic symbiosis paradigm of foreign direct investment to investigate interaction between the political and socio-economic spheres and their mutual dependence on and relationship with different players in the host country. By applying the paradigm to Dongguan, the political and socio-economic impetus to foreign investment and the resultant effects are illustrated together with the interaction between and the influence of the various players.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10767,'publisher',15,'Palgrave','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10768,'date',15,'2001','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10769,'type',15,'Book','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10770,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10771,'identifier',15,'Yeung, G (2001) Foreign Investment and Socio-economic Development in China: The Case of Dongguan. Studies on the Chinese economy (Palgrave (Firm)) . Palgrave, Basingstoke, UK. ISBN 9780333778258','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10772,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/119/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:119'),(10773,'title',15,'Foreign direct investment and investment environment in Dongguan Municipality of southern China','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10774,'creator',15,'Yeung, Godfrey','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10775,'subject',15,'G Geography (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10776,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10777,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10778,'description',15,'Based on 26 case studies, this paper investigates the socio-economic causes of the inflow of FDI and its policy implications in Dongguan. The favourable factors for foreign investors in Dongguan can be categorised under the Dunning\'s OLI (ownership, locational and internalisation advantages) framework. This paper argues that factors other than policy incentive, such as sub-contractual and pseudo integration, are playing more important roles in attracting the inflow of FDI and maintaining the high level of economic growth in Dongguan. This finding questions the effectiveness of policy incentives, such as tax-breaks, implemented by the Government as a means to attract FDI in Dongguan. The existence of \'Chinese crony capitalism\' calls for further improvement in the implementation of laws and regulations in Dongguan and the reduction of bureaucratic red-tape by the central and local governments.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10779,'publisher',15,'Taylor & Francis','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10780,'date',15,'2001-02','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10781,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10782,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10783,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10784,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/120/1/Dongguan.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10785,'identifier',15,'Yeung, Godfrey (2001) Foreign direct investment and investment environment in Dongguan Municipality of southern China. Journal of Contemporary China, 10 (26). pp. 125-154. ISSN 1067-0564','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10786,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/10670560125259 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10787,'relation',15,'10.1080/10670560125259 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10788,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/120/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:120'),(10789,'title',15,'Big Business with Chinese Characteristics: Two Paths to Growth of the Firm in China under Reform','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10790,'creator',15,'Nolan, P','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10791,'creator',15,'Yeung, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10792,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10793,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10794,'description',15,'This paper presents a case study of two large firms which emerged from among the ranks of traditional state-owned enterprises and new entrants: Shougang (steel) and Sanjiu (pharmaceuticals). Rather than being irreconcilable with the market economy, the experience of these two firms suggests that the Chinese Communist Party and the People\'s Liberation Army possessed a rich legacy of organisational and motivational skills. Moreover, Shougang and Sanjiu both grew rapidly through mergers and acquisitions in the absence of privatisation and a developed stock market. Furthermore, the main reason for Shougang and Sanjiu\'s success is not special help from the government or the army, but rather the fact that its leadership used their autonomy to construct a highly effective business organisation.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10795,'date',15,'2001-07-01','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10796,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10797,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10798,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10799,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/121/1/Sanjiu%2DShougang.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10800,'identifier',15,'Nolan, P and Yeung, G (2001) Big Business with Chinese Characteristics: Two Paths to Growth of the Firm in China under Reform. Cambridge Journal of Economics, 25 (4). pp. 443-465. ISSN 0309-166X','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10801,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/cje/25.4.443','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10802,'relation',15,'10.1093/cje/25.4.443','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10803,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/121/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:121'),(10804,'title',15,'Government Policy and Competitive Advantages of Foreign-Financed Firms in the Guangdong Province of Southern China','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10805,'creator',15,'Yeung, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10806,'creator',15,'Mok, V','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10807,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10808,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10809,'description',15,'This paper investigates the impact of various Chinese government policies on the competitive advantages of foreign-financed manufacturing firms in Guangdong province of southern China. The objectives of various government sector-specific policies are to lubricate the factor markets in labour, capital and products and to facilitate the operation of foreign-financed firms. However, the actual effects are often quite different: the ambiguity, complexity and inflexibility of policies impose higher transaction costs on foreign-financed firms. These disadvantages offset some economic benefits gained under the central government\'s preferential foreign direct investment policy and thus damages the competitive advantages of foreign-financed firms based in Guangdong. Worse still, the lack of co-ordination among various bureaux further hampers arbitration between government bureaux and foreign investors.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10810,'date',15,'2002-08','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10811,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10812,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10813,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10814,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/122/1/Goverment_Intervention_%26_FDI.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10815,'identifier',15,'Yeung, G and Mok, V (2002) Government Policy and Competitive Advantages of Foreign-Financed Firms in the Guangdong Province of Southern China. Asian Business & Management, 1 (2). pp. 227-247. ISSN 1472-4782','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10816,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1057/palgrave.abm.9200013','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10817,'relation',15,'10.1057/palgrave.abm.9200013','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10818,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/122/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:122'),(10819,'title',15,'WTO Accession and Managerial Challenges for Manufacturing Sectors in Southern China','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10820,'creator',15,'Yeung, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10821,'creator',15,'Mok, V','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10822,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10823,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10824,'description',15,'Based on 31 case studies, this study tests the validity of four major managerial hypotheses for manufacturers in China after WTO accession. It is argued that the skills of managers will be severely tested in four specific areas after China accedes to the WTO: (1) preparing for trade disputes with their overseas competitors, (2) developing newer and higher value-added products and diversifying their markets, (3) selecting the appropriate localization strategy, and (4) upgrading manufacturing processes and work practices to comply with international (and regional) standards, as well as being aware of overseas competitors using these standards as non-trade barriers. Managers also have to strike a delicate balance to deal with these interrelated challenges under the constraints of time and available resources. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10825,'publisher',15,'Taylor & Francis','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10826,'date',15,'2002','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10827,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10828,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10829,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10830,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/123/1/Management_%26_WTO_Accession.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10831,'identifier',15,'Yeung, G and Mok, V (2002) WTO Accession and Managerial Challenges for Manufacturing Sectors in Southern China. Asia Pacific Business Review, 9 (2). pp. 158-183. ISSN 1360-2381','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10832,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/713999179 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10833,'relation',15,'10.1080/713999179 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10834,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/123/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:123'),(10835,'title',15,'An internalization approach to joint ventures: the case of Coca-Cola in China','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10836,'creator',15,'Mok, Vincent','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10837,'creator',15,'Dai, Xiudian','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10838,'creator',15,'Yeung, Godfrey','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10839,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10840,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10841,'description',15,'In the presence of high transaction costs due to market imperfections, it is normally less expensive for multinational corporations (MNCs) to conduct their business activities in new markets through their internal corporate structures rather than by relying on the markets. Based on a case study of Coca-Cola\'s entry into the Chinese market, this paper tests the applicability of internalization theory to explaining the entry mode choices of MNCs in developing countries. Internalization theory reveals the economic rationale that was behind the changes in Coca-Cola\'s modes of entry as it moved from franchising to joint ventures (JVs) with selected local partners, and more recently to the combination of JVs and franchising. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10842,'publisher',15,'Taylor & Francis','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10843,'date',15,'2002-10','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10844,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10845,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10846,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10847,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/124/1/Coca_Cola.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10848,'identifier',15,'Mok, Vincent, Dai, Xiudian and Yeung, Godfrey (2002) An internalization approach to joint ventures: the case of Coca-Cola in China. Asia Pacific Business Review, 9 (1). pp. 39-58. ISSN 1360-2381','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10849,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/713999168 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10850,'relation',15,'10.1080/713999168 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10851,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/124/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:124'),(10852,'title',15,'The implications of WTO Accession on the Pharmaceutical Industry in China','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10853,'creator',15,'Yeung, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10854,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10855,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10856,'description',15,'Given the limited capabilities of R&D and global distribution channels, and the virtual non-existence of patented drugs, the Chinese pharmaceutical industry has little chance to enter the global market of Western prescription drugs and compete with the established global giants head-on. The reality is that they are chasing a moving target and their competitors are becoming bigger and stronger day by day. The substantial reduction of import tariffs and the granting of comprehensive trading and distribution rights to foreign-financed firms following WTO accession, effectively tilted the level-playing field against the Chinese pharmaceutical industry. Given the short-term competitive advantages of the Chinese pharmaceutical industry on Chinese drugs, three development strategies are suggested: (1) consolidate the local market of herbal and generic drugs; (2) market Chinese drugs via the Internet; and (3) outsource R&D and collaborative marketing. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10857,'date',15,'2002-08','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10858,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10859,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10860,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10861,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/125/1/WTO_Accession_%26_Pharmaceutical_Industry.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10862,'identifier',15,'Yeung, G (2002) The implications of WTO Accession on the Pharmaceutical Industry in China. Journal of Contemporary China, 11 (32). pp. 473-493. ISSN 1067-0564','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10863,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/10670560220152292 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10864,'relation',15,'10.1080/10670560220152292 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10865,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/125/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:125'),(10866,'title',15,'WTO accession, the Changing Competitiveness of Foreign-Financed Firms and Regional Development in Guangdong of Southern China','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10867,'creator',15,'Yeung, G','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10868,'subject',15,'G Geography (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10869,'subject',15,'HD0028 Management. Industrial Management','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10870,'subject',15,'H Social Sciences (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10871,'subject',15,'JF Political institutions (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10872,'description',15,'This paper investigates the changing competitiveness of foreign-financed manufacturing firms and its implications for regional development in Guangdong province of southern China in the run-up to World Trade Organization (WTO) accession. It is argued that transnational corporations (TNCs) and some competitive, large-scale, locally-funded firms in Guangdong will triumph after WTO accession. The crowding-out process of small and medium sized enterprises (SMEs) in Guangdong will be accelerated in the near future, as they are competing directly with TNCs, and as their competitive advantages are diminishing, due to bureaucratic red tape and the rigorous enforcement of new government policies. Due to close business linkages with local privately-funded firms, the competitiveness and vitality of foreign-financed enterprises will have profound long term effects on the economic development of Guangdong, before and after WTO accession.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10873,'date',15,'2002-08','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10874,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10875,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10876,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10877,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/126/1/WTO_Accession_%26_FDI.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10878,'identifier',15,'Yeung, G (2002) WTO accession, the Changing Competitiveness of Foreign-Financed Firms and Regional Development in Guangdong of Southern China. Regional Studies, 36 (6). pp. 627-642. ISSN 0034-3404','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10879,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/00343400220146786 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10880,'relation',15,'10.1080/00343400220146786 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10881,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/126/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:126'),(10882,'title',15,'S