UK women academics and managers on quality and power in higher education, this article interrogates the impact of quality assurance discourses and practices on women in higher education. Micro-level analysis of the effects of audit and the evaluative state seem to suggest that hegemonic masculinities and gendered power relations are being reinforced by the emphasis on competition, targets, audit trails and performance (Morley, 2003a). Furthermore, pedagogic space for exploring social justice issues is closing with the emphasis on learning outcomes and student consumerism (Morley, 2003b). Yet women are also gaining new visibility as a consequence of the creation of a new cadre of quality managers. Quality assurance, as a regime of power, appears to offer both repressive and creative potential for women. This article will explore whether quality signs and practices are gendered and whether these represent opportunity or exploitation for women in the academy. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10989,'date',15,'2005-10','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10990,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10991,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10992,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10993,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/185/1/gender_and_education.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10994,'identifier',15,'Morley, L. (2005) Opportunity or Exploitation: Women and Quality Assurance in Higher Education. Gender and Education, 17 (4). pp. 411-429. ISSN 0954-0253','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10995,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/09540250500145106','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10996,'relation',15,'10.1080/09540250500145106','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10997,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/185/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:185'),(10998,'title',15,'Sounds, Silences and Contradictions: Gender Equity in Commonwealth Higher Education - Clare Burton Memorial Lecture 2003','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(10999,'creator',15,'Morley, L.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11000,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11001,'description',15,'No Abstract Available','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11002,'date',15,'2005-10','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11003,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11004,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11005,'identifier',15,'Morley, L. (2005) Sounds, Silences and Contradictions: Gender Equity in Commonwealth Higher Education - Clare Burton Memorial Lecture 2003. Australian Feminist Studies, 20 (46). pp. 109-119. ISSN 0816-4649','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11006,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0816464042000334573 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11007,'relation',15,'10.1080/0816464042000334573 ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11008,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/186/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:186'),(11009,'title',15,'Researching Women: An Annotated Bibliography on Gender Equity in Commonwealth Higher Education','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11010,'creator',15,'Morley, L.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11011,'creator',15,'Sorhaindo, A','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11012,'creator',15,'Burke, PJ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11013,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11014,'description',15,'This annotated bibliography documents the wealth of scholarship on gender and higher education in the Commonwealth, particularly in low-income countries. It contains the results of a major literature search of published and \'grey\' literature: the texts that do not reach the public domain, including conference papers, seminar papers and MA and doctoral theses. The aim is to present as full a picture as possible of issues, debates and concerns that have arisen over the past ten years. The bibliography originated in the Gender Equity in Commonwealth Higher Education Research Project, directed by Louise Morley at the Institute of Education, University of London. In the early stages of the project it became apparent that there is a paucity of published literature on women and higher education outside the West. While there is literature on girls and education in low-income countries, there appeared to be little material published about women\'s experiences of higher education, depsite the research on gender equity in higher education across the Commonwealth. Somehow descriptions and analysis of this work did not seem to be getting into the public domain. This meant that opportunities for dissemination and sharing were being severely limited. Researching Women addresses this lack by describing the location and reviewing the content of writing from Africa, Asia, the Caribbean, Australasia and the UK. As such, it should be a valuable resource for gender scholars who are interested in international patterns and interventions for gender equity in higher education. ','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11015,'publisher',15,'Institute of Education','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11016,'date',15,'2005','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11017,'type',15,'Book','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11018,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11019,'identifier',15,'Morley, L., Sorhaindo, A and Burke, PJ (2005) Researching Women: An Annotated Bibliography on Gender Equity in Commonwealth Higher Education. Institute of Education, London, UK. ISBN 9780854737147','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11020,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/187/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:187'),(11021,'title',15,'Gender Equity in Commonwealth Higher Education','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11022,'creator',15,'Morley, L.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11023,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11024,'description',15,'This article explores emerging themes from the literature on gender and higher education in low-income Commonwealth countries. It attempts to engage with a range of unpublished or \'grey\' literature and to identify aspects of gender inequality that universally disturb and discomfort. The dominant literature in the field of gender and higher education is from the UK, USA, Northern Europe, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand. Yet there is considerable gender equity activity also in low-income Commonwealth countries. But the nature of gendered change or obstacles to gender equality in higher education have not been systematically mapped across the Commonwealth and there has been an absence of multilateral dissemination. The article highlights how gender has been excluded as a category of analysis in writing on the changing political economy of higher education and the development of borderless provision.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11025,'date',15,'2005-06','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11026,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11027,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11028,'identifier',15,'Morley, L. (2005) Gender Equity in Commonwealth Higher Education. Women\'s Studies International Forum, 28 (2-3). pp. 209-221. ISSN 0277-5395','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11029,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.wsif.2005.04.008','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11030,'relation',15,'10.1016/j.wsif.2005.04.008','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11031,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/188/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:188'),(11032,'title',15,'The Micropolitics of Quality','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11033,'creator',15,'Morley, L.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11034,'subject',15,'L Education (General)','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11035,'description',15,'This paper discusses how the audit culture has impacted on UK academics in terms of professional identities, priorities and social relations. Micropolitics, performativity, psychic economy and the changing political economy of higher education are some of the theoretical tools used to offer some explanatory power for the range of engagements with quality assurance. Questions are raised about the polysemic discourse of quality and how it has been subjected to multiple interpretations. For example, there are those members of the academy who see it as a major form of modernisation and student empowerment, while others see it as a form of symbolic violence. Specific attention is paid to peer review, impact studies, gendered power relations, productivity measures and whether quality intersects with equality in the academy. The paper concludes with calls to consider what the gestalt is of higher education.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11036,'date',15,'2005-07','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11037,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11038,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11039,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11040,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/189/1/micropolitics_of_quality.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11041,'identifier',15,'Morley, L. (2005) The Micropolitics of Quality. Critical Quarterly, 47 (1-2). pp. 83-95. ISSN 0011-1562','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11042,'relation',15,'http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.0011-1562.2005.00616.x','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11043,'relation',15,'10.1111/j.0011-1562.2005.00616.x','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11044,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/189/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:189'),(11045,'title',15,'Properhood','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11046,'creator',15,'Coates, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11047,'subject',15,'P Philology. Linguistics','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11048,'description',15,'A history of the notion of PROPERHOOD in philosophy and linguistics is given. Two long-standing ideas, (i) that proper names have no sense, and (ii) that they are expressions whose purpose is to refer to individuals, cannot be made to work comprehensively while PROPER is understood as a subcategory of linguistic units, whether of lexemes or phrases. Phrases of the type the old vicarage, which are potentially ambiguous with regard to properhood, encourage the suggestion that PROPER is best understood as mode of reference contrasting with SEMANTIC reference; in the former, the intension/sense of any lexical items within the referring expression, and any entailments they give rise to, are canceled. PROPER NAMES are all those expressions that refer nonintensionally. Linguistic evidence is given that this opposition can be grammaticalized, speculation is made about its neurological basis, and psycholinguistic evidence is adduced in support. The PROPER NOUN,asa lexical category, is argued to be epiphenomenal on proper names as newly defined. Some consequences of the view that proper names have no sense in the act of reference are explored; they are not debarred from having senses (better: synchronic etymologies) accessible during other (meta)linguistic activities.','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11049,'date',15,'2006-06','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11050,'type',15,'Article','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11051,'type',15,'PeerReviewed','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11052,'format',15,'application/pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11053,'identifier',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/196/1/Properhood.pdf','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11054,'identifier',15,'Coates, R (2006) Properhood. Language, 82 (2). pp. 356-382. ISSN 0097-8507','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11055,'relation',15,'http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/196/','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:196'),(11056,'title',15,'Citizenship, Communities and Adult Learning','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11057,'creator',15,'Coare, Pamela','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11058,'creator',15,'Johnston, Rennie','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11059,'subject',15,'LC5201 Education extension. Adult education. Continuing education','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11060,'subject',15,'LB2300 Higher education','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11061,'publisher',15,'Institute of Education, University of Stirling','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11062,'contributor',15,'Edwards, R','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11063,'contributor',15,'Gray, P','oai:sro.sussex.ac.uk:204'),(11064,'contributor',15,'Morgan-Klein, B','oai:sro.susse