gi, D. V., Magnoli, F. C. and Goncalves-de-Andrade, R. M. 2007.  Loxosceles spider venom induces the release of thrombomodulin and Endothelial Protein C Receptor: implications for the pathogenesis of intravascular coagulation as observed in loxoscelism. J Thromb Haemost 5  , pp. 989-995.  10.1111/j.1538-7836.2007.02382.x <http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1538-7836.2007.02382.x>                    ','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:62'),(20870,'relation',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/62/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:62'),(20871,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=17229042','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:62'),(20872,'relation',13,'10.1111/j.1538-7836.2007.02382.x','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:62'),(20873,'title',13,'C-reactive protein-induced in vitro vasorelaxation is an artefact caused by the presence of sodium azide in commercial preparations','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20874,'creator',13,'Van Den Berg, Carmen Wilma','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20875,'creator',13,'Taylor, Karolina E.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20876,'creator',13,'Lang, Derek','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20877,'description',13,'OBJECTIVE: Although C-reactive protein (CRP) is increasingly recognized as an independent risk factor for acute myocardial events, recent evidence suggests that it can directly induce vasorelaxation. This study aimed to investigate the mechanism of this CRP-induced response. METHODS AND RESULTS: Isometric tension recordings were used to measure endothelium-dependent and endothelium-independent vascular smooth muscle relaxation in isolated rabbit aortic rings. CRP generated in-house by genetic engineering and expressed in Chinese hamster ovary cells, CRP purified from ascites, and CRP obtained from commercial sources were assessed for vasorelaxing properties. Only the commercial CRP preparation induced vasorelaxation; more than half maximal relaxation was observed at 0.025 microg/mL and maximum relaxation attained at 0.25 microg/mL. Commercial CRP contains high levels of sodium azide, a well-known vasorelaxant. Removal of this agent by dialysis abolished the vasodilatory effect of commercial CRP. Sodium azide alone at concentrations equivalent to that present in the commercial CRP produced a near-identical relaxation pattern to the undialyzed commercial product. CONCLUSIONS: CRP has no vasorelaxant properties per se, and the reported vasorelaxant ability of CRP is an artifact caused by sodium azide present in commercial preparations of this agent.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20878,'date',13,'2004-08-01','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20879,'type',13,'Article','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20880,'type',13,'PeerReviewed','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20881,'identifier',13,'       Van Den Berg, Carmen Wilma <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A0389071.html>, Taylor, Karolina E. and Lang, Derek <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A000203U.html> 2004.  C-reactive protein-induced in vitro vasorelaxation is an artefact caused by the presence of sodium azide in commercial preparations. Arteriosclerosis Thrombosis and Vascular Biology 24  (10)  , e168-171.  10.1161/01.ATV.0000142807.92781.d9 <http://dx.doi.org/10.1161/01.ATV.0000142807.92781.d9>                    ','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20882,'relation',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/63/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20883,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=15319265','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20884,'relation',13,'10.1161/01.ATV.0000142807.92781.d9','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:63'),(20885,'title',13,'A model of the putative pore region of the cardiac ryanodine receptor channel','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20886,'creator',13,'Welch, William','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20887,'creator',13,'Rheault, Shana','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20888,'creator',13,'West, Duncan J.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20889,'creator',13,'Williams, Alan John','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20890,'subject',13,'R Medicine (General)','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20891,'description',13,'Using the bacterial K+ channel KcsA as a template, we constructed models of the pore region of the cardiac ryanodine receptor channel (RyR2) monomer and tetramer. Physicochemical characteristics of the RyR2 model monomer were compared with the template, including homology, predicted secondary structure, surface area, hydrophobicity, and electrostatic potential. Values were comparable with those of KcsA. Monomers of the RyR2 model were minimized and assembled into a tetramer that was, in turn, minimized. The assembled tetramer adopts a structure equivalent to that of KcsA with a central pore. Characteristics of the RyR2 model tetramer were compared with the KcsA template, including average empirical energy, strain energy, solvation free energy, solvent accessibility, and hydrophobic, polar, acid, and base moments. Again, values for the model and template were comparable. The pores of KcsA and RyR2 have a common motif with a hydrophobic channel that becomes polar at both entrances. Quantitative comparisons indicate that the assembled structure provides a plausible model for the pore of RyR2. Movement of Ca2+, K+, and tetraethylammonium (TEA+) through the model RyR2 pore were simulated with explicit solvation. These simulations suggest that the model RyR2 pore is permeable to Ca2+ and K+ with rates of translocation greater for K+. In contrast, simulations indicate that tetraethylammonium blocks movement of metal cations.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20892,'date',13,'2004-01-01','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20893,'type',13,'Article','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20894,'type',13,'PeerReviewed','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20895,'format',13,'application/pdf','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20896,'identifier',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/64/1/modelofputativepore.pdf','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:64'),(20897,'identifier