c.uk/93/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:93'),(21391,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=14612902','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:93'),(21392,'relation',13,'10.1038/sj.bjc.6601359','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:93'),(21393,'title',13,'Different combinations of biallelic APC mutation confer different growth advantages in colorectal tumours','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21394,'creator',13,'Cheadle, Jeremy Peter','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21395,'creator',13,'Krawczak, Michael','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21396,'creator',13,'Thomas, Meinir W','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21397,'creator',13,'Hodges, Angela Kaye','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21398,'creator',13,'Al-Tassan, Nada','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21399,'creator',13,'Fleming, Nick','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21400,'creator',13,'Sampson, Julian Roy','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21401,'subject',13,'R Medicine (General)','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21402,'description',13,'New facets to Knudson\'s [corrected] \"two-hit\" hypothesis have been proposed recently in relation to adenomatous polyposis coli (APC): protein inactivation may be selected weakly, and the two hits may be interdependent. We reviewed published data on 165 sporadic and 102 familial adenomatous polyposis-associated colorectal tumors with two characterized mutations. Using a Poisson model, we redefined the mutation cluster region (MCR) to residues 1281-1556 and confirmed that the locations of pairs of APC mutations are interdependent (P < 0.0001). A mathematical model, based on the data for sporadic tumors, implied different growth advantages for different combinations of APC mutations: genotype I/I (I: mutation inside MCR) was 3.9 times more likely to be selected than IO or IL (O: mutation outside MCR, L: allelic loss), which were 27.8 times more likely to be selected than OO or OL.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21403,'publisher',13,'American Association for Cancer Research','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21404,'date',13,'2002-01-15','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21405,'type',13,'Article','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21406,'type',13,'PeerReviewed','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21407,'identifier',13,'       Cheadle, Jeremy Peter <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A0702554.html>, Krawczak, Michael, Thomas, Meinir W, Hodges, Angela Kaye, Al-Tassan, Nada, Fleming, Nick and Sampson, Julian Roy <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A0160820.html> 2002.  Different combinations of biallelic APC mutation confer different growth advantages in colorectal tumours. Cancer Research 62  , pp. 363-366.                      ','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21408,'relation',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/94/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21409,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=11809680','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:94'),(21410,'title',13,'Intensive induction chemotherapy with CBOP/BEP in patients with poor prognosis germ cell tumors','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21411,'creator',13,'Christian, J. A.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21412,'creator',13,'Huddart, R. A.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21413,'creator',13,'Norman, A.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21414,'creator',13,'Mason, Malcolm David','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21415,'creator',13,'Fossa, S.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21416,'creator',13,'Aass, N.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21417,'creator',13,'Nicholl, E. J.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21418,'creator',13,'Dearnaley, David P.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21419,'creator',13,'Horwich, A.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21420,'subject',13,'R Medicine (General)','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21421,'description',13,'Purpose: Despite a high cure rate in patients with testicular cancer, there remain patients in the poor prognosis group who have a less favorable outcome. Intensive induction chemotherapy using a regimen consisting of carboplatin, bleomycin, vincristine, and cisplatin, followed by bleomycin, etoposide, and cisplatin (CBOP/BEP), developed at the Royal Marsden Hospital, is designed to overcome the rapid proliferation seen in germ cell tumors. This study assesses the outcome of patients with poor-prognosis nonseminomatous germ cell tumors (NSGCT) treated with CBOP/BEP. \r\n\r\nPatients and Methods: Patients with NSGCT from three centers, classified as poor prognosis according to International Germ Cell Classification Consensus Group criteria, were treated with CBOP/BEP regimen during the period from 1989 to 2000. Data on treatment toxicity, relapse-free survival (RFS), and overall survival (OS) were collected prospectively on a hospital database. \r\n\r\nResults: Fifty-four male patients with poor prognosis NSGCT were treated with CBOP/BEP. The RFS at 3 and 5 years for all patients was 83.2% (95% confidence interval [CI], 68.8% to 91.3%). After a median follow-up of 4 years, the OS of the 54 patients was 91.5% (95% CI, 78.6% to 96.8%) at 3 years and 87.6% (95% CI, 71.3% to 94.9%) at 5 years. Three-year OS in patients with a primary mediastinal germ cell tumor was 77.1% (95% CI, 34.5% to 93.9%) compared with 95.4% (95% CI, 82.8% to 98.8%) in patients with a testicular primary tumor (P = .24). \r\n\r\nConclusion: The results reported here compare favorably with the historical results of alternative regimens used in the management of poor-prognosis NSGCT. We suggest a phase III trial to confirm our findings.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21422,'date',13,'2003-03-01','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21423,'type',13,'Article','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21424,'type',13,'PeerReviewed','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21425,'identifier',13,'       Christian, J. A., Huddart, R. A., Norman, A., Mason, Malcolm David <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A008319Q.html>, Fossa, S., Aass, N., Nicholl, E. J., Dearnaley, David P. and Horwich, A. 2003.  Intensive induction chemotherapy with CBOP/BEP in patients with poor prognosis germ cell tumors. Journal of Clinical Oncology 21  (5)  , pp. 871-877.  10.1200/JCO.2003.05.155 <http://dx.doi.org/10.1200/JCO.2003.05.155>                    ','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21426,'relation',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/95/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21427,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=12610187','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21428,'relation',13,'10.1200/JCO.2003.05.155','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:95'),(21429,'title',13,'Recovery of CD8+ T-cell function during systemic chemotherapy in advanced ovarian cancer','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21430,'creator',13,'Coleman, Sharon Louise','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21431,'creator',13,'Clayton, Aled','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21432,'creator',13,'Mason, Malcolm David','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21433,'creator',13,'Jasani, Bharat','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21434,'creator',13,'Adams, Malcolm','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21435,'creator',13,'Tabi, Zsuzsanna','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21436,'subject',13,'RC0254 Neoplasms. Tumors. Oncology (including Cancer)','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21437,'description',13,'Immunologic approaches are emerging as new treatment options in several types of cancer. However, whereas the ability of patients to develop potent CD8+ T-cell responses is crucial for efficient antitumor responses, immunocompetence and T-cell function are not tested routinely in patients entering immunotherapy. The objective of our study was to monitor T-cell function in advanced cancer and during chemotherapy. CD8+ T-cell function of 21 patients with advanced ovarian cancer (stages III-IV) was assessed by cytokine flow cytometry following stimulation of 42 PBMC samples with a panel of synthetic viral peptides in vitro, consisting of pan-Caucasian epitopes. CD8+ T-cell responses were significantly lower in patients with high levels (>200 units/mL) of Ca125 (marker of tumor load and progression) than in those with low Ca125 levels (P = 0.0013). In longitudinal studies of nine patients, chemotherapy was associated with decreasing Ca125 levels in seven cases and also with improvement or maintenance of CD8+ T-cell function in seven cases. After the full course of chemotherapy, five of nine patients in remission displayed potent CD8+ T-cell responses, whereas four of nine patients in progression displayed low or decreasing T-cell responses, pointing toward a correlation between T-cell function and clinical response. Our results show for the first time that CD8+ T-cell function is not permanently suppressed in advanced cancer and successful chemotherapy is associated with improved antigen-specific T-cell reactivity. We suggest that functional assays determining T-cell immunocompetence can be valuable tools for optimizing cancer immunotherapy for improved clinical success.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21438,'date',13,'2005-08-01','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21439,'type',13,'Article','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21440,'type',13,'PeerReviewed','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21441,'identifier',13,'       Coleman, Sharon Louise <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A062125O.html>, Clayton, Aled <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A062480N.html>, Mason, Malcolm David <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A008319Q.html>, Jasani, Bharat, Adams, Malcolm and Tabi, Zsuzsanna <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A047027C.html> 2005.  Recovery of CD8+ T-cell function during systemic chemotherapy in advanced ovarian cancer. Cancer Research 65  (15)  , pp. 7000-7006.  10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-04-3792 <http://dx.doi.org/10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-04-3792>                    ','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21442,'relation',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/96/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21443,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=16061686','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21444,'relation',13,'10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-04-3792','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:96'),(21445,'title',13,'A double-blind, placebo-controlled, randomized trial of oral sodium clodronate for metastatic prostate cancer (MRC PR05 Trial)','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21446,'creator',13,'Dearnaley, David P.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21447,'creator',13,'Sydes, Matthew R.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21448,'creator',13,'Mason, Malcolm David','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21449,'creator',13,'Stott, Mark','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21450,'creator',13,'Powell, Christopher S.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21451,'creator',13,'Robinson, Anne C. R.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21452,'creator',13,'Thompson, Peter M.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21453,'creator',13,'Moffat, Leslie E.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21454,'creator',13,'Naylor, Sharon L.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21455,'creator',13,'Parmar, Mahesh K. B.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21456,'date',13,'2003-09-03','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21457,'type',13,'Article','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21458,'type',13,'PeerReviewed','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21459,'identifier',13,'       Dearnaley, David P., Sydes, Matthew R., Mason, Malcolm David <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A008319Q.html>, Stott, Mark, Powell, Christopher S., Robinson, Anne C. R., Thompson, Peter M., Moffat, Leslie E., Naylor, Sharon L. and Parmar, Mahesh K. B. 2003.  A double-blind, placebo-controlled, randomized trial of oral sodium clodronate for metastatic prostate cancer (MRC PR05 Trial). J Natl Cancer Inst 95  (17)  , pp. 1300-11.  10.1093/jnci/djg038 <http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/jnci/djg038>                    ','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21460,'relation',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/97/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21461,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=12953084','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21462,'relation',13,'10.1093/jnci/djg038','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:97'),(21463,'title',13,'Mcm2, Geminin, and KI67 define proliferative state and are prognostic markers in renal cell carcinoma','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21464,'creator',13,'Dudderidge, Tim J.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21465,'creator',13,'Stoeber, Kai','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21466,'creator',13,'Loddo, Marco','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21467,'creator',13,'Atkinson, Geraldine','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21468,'creator',13,'Fanshawe, Thomas','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21469,'creator',13,'Griffiths, David Francis Rees','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21470,'creator',13,'Williams, Gareth H.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21471,'description',13,'Purpose: The origin licensing factors minichromosome maintenance 2 (Mcm2) and Geminin have recently been identified as critical regulators of growth and differentiation. Here we have investigated the regulation of these licensing factors together with Ki67 to further elucidate the cell cycle kinetics of renal cell carcinoma (RCC). Furthermore, we have examined the role of Ki67, Mcm2, and Geminin in disease-free survival after nephrectomy in patients with localized RCC. \r\n\r\nExperimental Design: Tissue sections from 176 radical nephrectomy specimens were immunohistochemically stained with Mcm2, Geminin, and Ki67 antibodies. Labeling indices (LI) for these markers were compared with clinicopathologic parameters (median follow-up 44 months). \r\n\r\nResults: In RCC, Mcm2 is expressed at much higher levels than Ki-67 and Geminin, respectively [medians 41.6%, 7.3%, and 3.5% (P < 0.001)] and was most closely linked to tumor grade (P < 0.001). For each marker, Kaplan-Meier survival curves provided strong evidence that increased expression is associated with reduced disease-free survival time (P < 0.001). Additionally, an Mcm2  Ki67 LI identified a unique licensed but nonproliferating population of tumor cells that increased significantly with tumor grade (P = 0.004) and was also of prognostic value (P = 0.01). On multivariate analysis, grade, vascular invasion, capsular invasion, Ki67 LI >12%, and age were found to be independent prognostic markers. \r\n\r\nConclusions: Although Ki67 is identified as an independent prognostic marker, semiquantitative assessment is difficult due to the very low proliferative fraction identified by this marker. In contrast, Mcm2 identifies an increased growth fraction that is closely linked to grade, provides prognostic information, and is amenable to semiquantitative analysis in routine pathologic assessment.','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21472,'date',13,'2005-04-01','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21473,'type',13,'Article','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21474,'type',13,'PeerReviewed','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21475,'identifier',13,'       Dudderidge, Tim J., Stoeber, Kai, Loddo, Marco, Atkinson, Geraldine, Fanshawe, Thomas, Griffiths, David Francis Rees <http://orca.cf.ac.uk/view/cardiffauthors/A0078184.html> and Williams, Gareth H. 2005.  Mcm2, Geminin, and KI67 define proliferative state and are prognostic markers in renal cell carcinoma. Clinical cancer research 11  (7)  , pp. 2510-2517.  10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-04-1776 <http://dx.doi.org/10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-04-1776>                    ','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21476,'relation',13,'http://orca.cf.ac.uk/98/','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21477,'relation',13,'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&dopt=Citation&list_uids=15814627','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21478,'relation',13,'10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-04-1776','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:98'),(21479,'title',13,'No evidence that FLT3 status should be considered as an indicator for transplantation in acute myeloid leukemia (AML): an analysis of 1135 patients, excluding acute promyelocytic leukemia, from the UK MRC AML10 and 12 trials','oai:http://orca.cf.ac.uk:99'),(21480,